{"title_page": "Haq Nawaz Jhangvi", "text_new": "{{Infobox religious biography\n|name = Haq Nawaz Jhangvi\n|nationality = [[Pakistani]]\n}}\n'''Haq Nawaz Jhangvi''' ({{lang-ur|\u062d\u0642 \u0646\u0648\u0627\u0632 \u062c\u06be\u0646\u06af\u0648\u06cc}}, ''\u1e24aq Naw\u0101z Jhangv\u012b''; 1952&nbsp;&ndash; 23 February 1990) was a [[Pakistani people|Pakistani]] cleric who founded the [[Sipah-e-Sahaba|Anjumane Sipahe Sahaba]] on 6 September 1986.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pakistan's  sectarian terrorist groups|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/1758534.stm|accessdate=11 December 2012|newspaper=BBC News|date=13 January 2002}}</ref>\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Haq Nawaz Jhangvi.jpg|thumb|right|Haq Nawaz Jhangvi Shaheed]] -->\n\n==Biography==\nHaq Nawaz was born in 1952 in Chela, a village in the [[Jhang District]] of [[Punjab, Pakistan]]. His father name is Wali Muhammad Sipra. He graduated from the Jamia Khair al-Madaris in [[Multan]] in 1971. Haq Nawaz joined the [[Jamiat Ulama-e-Islam]] and started teaching at a [[madrasah]] in [[Toba Tek Singh]] in 1972. In 1973 he became the [[imam]] and [[khatib]] of a mosque in ''[[mohalla]]'' Piplianwala in the city of [[Jhang Saddar]]. Before he began focusing his preaching against Shia, he was active in the [[Khatm-i Nabuwwat]] movement against Qaadiyanis.<ref name=abouzahab>{{cite book|last=Abou-Zahab|first=Mariam|author-link1=Mariam Abou Zahab|editor1-last=Ahmad|editor1-first=Imtiaz|editor2-last=Reifeld|editor2-first=Helmut|title=Lived Islam in South Asia: Adaptation, Accommodation & Conflict|year=2004|publisher=Social Science Press|location=Jor Bagh, New Delhi|isbn=8187358157|chapter=The Sunni-Shia Conflict in Jhang (Pakistan)}}</ref>\n\nAfter the 1979 [[Iranian Revolution]], Jhangvi began attacking the [[Islamic Republic of Iran]] by accusing it of exporting its revolution. He directed his attacks against Shia beliefs and civilians, as well as against [[Ayatollah Khomeini]], Iran's [[Supreme Leader of Iran|Supreme Leader]]. Locally, he targeted the Shah Jewna family and the district administration and became extremely popular among local residents.<ref name=abouzahab/> Jhangvi also began preaching and became popular among  Sunnis, who were willing to support him in his cause. He became vocal against local Shias.<ref name=abouzahab/> Jhangvi founded Anjuman-i Sipah-i Sahabah in Jhang on 6 September 1985.<ref name=abouzahab/><ref>{{cite book|last1=Murphy|first1=Eamon|title=The Making of Terrorism in Pakistan: Historical and Social Roots of Extremism|date=2013|publisher=Routledge|pages=129, 131|url=https://books.google.com/?id=19mPVOBZ_9YC&dq=haq+nawaz+jhangvi+wahhabi|accessdate=4 May 2016|isbn=9780415565264}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 February 1990, he was asaassinated by unknown militants. His funeral prayer was offered on Friday 23 February 1990 after Namaz e asar. He was buried in Jamia Mehmoodiya Jhang.{{cn|date=January 2019}} Sipah e sahaba members [[Riaz Basra]] and [[Akram Lahori]] formed their own organization in 1996, [[Lashkar-e-Jhangvi]], which was named after Haq Nawaz Jhangvi.{{cn|date=January 2019}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n===Books by him===\n*''K\u0332h\u0332ut\u0324b\u0101t-i am\u012br-i \u02bbaz\u012bmat : b\u0101n\u012b-i Sip\u0101h-i \u1e62a\u1e25\u0101bah Maul\u0101n\u0101 \u1e24aq Nav\u0101z Jhangv\u012b k\u012b ma\u02bbrikatul\u0101r\u0101\u02bc taq\u0101r\u012br k\u0101 majm\u016b\u02bbah''. Collections of speeches.\n===Books about him===\n*''Am\u012br-i \u02bbAz\u012bmat : \u1e25ay\u0101t'' by Mu\u1e25ammad Ily\u0101s B\u0101l\u0101ko\u1e6d\u012b.\n*''Maz\u0332hab ahl al-Sunnat va-al-Jam\u0101\u02bbat aur Maul\u0101n\u0101 \u1e24aq Nav\u0101z Jhangv\u012b k\u012b shah\u0101dat'' by Q\u0101\u1e93\u012b Maz\u0324har \u1e24usain.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Azam Tariq (religious leader)|Azam Tariq]]\n* [[Isar-ul-Haq Qasmi]]\n*[[Malik Ishaq]]\n*[[Moavia Azam Tariq]]\n*[[Masroor Nawaz Jhangvi]]\n*[[Riaz Basra]]\n*[[Zia ur rehman farooqi]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jhangvi, Haq Nawaz}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:1990 deaths]]\n[[Category:Assassinated religious leaders]]\n[[Category:Pakistani religious leaders]]\n[[Category:People from Jhang District]]\n[[Category:Deobandis]]\n[[Category:Shia\u2013Sunni sectarian violence in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Critics of Ahmadiyya]]\n[[Category:Pakistani Islamists]]\n[[Category:Pakistani far-right politicians]]\n\n{{Pakistan-reli-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox religious biography\n|name = Haq Nawaz Jhangvi\n|nationality = [[Pakistani]]\n}}\n'''Haq Nawaz Jhangvi''' ({{lang-ur|\u062d\u0642 \u0646\u0648\u0627\u0632 \u062c\u06be\u0646\u06af\u0648\u06cc}}, ''\u1e24aq Naw\u0101z Jhangv\u012b''; 1952&nbsp;&ndash; 23 February 1990) was a [[Pakistani people|Pakistani]] cleric who founded the [[Sipah-e-Sahaba|Anjumane Sipahe Sahaba]] on 6 September 1986.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pakistan's  sectarian terrorist groups|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/1758534.stm|accessdate=11 December 2012|newspaper=BBC News|date=13 January 2002}}</ref>\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Haq Nawaz Jhangvi.jpg|thumb|right|Haq Nawaz Jhangvi Shaheed]] -->\n\n==Biography==\nHaq Nawaz was born, in 1952 in Chela, a village in the [[Jhang District]] of [[Punjab, Pakistan]]. His father name is Wali Muhammad Sipra. He graduated from the Jamia Khair al-Madaris in [[Multan]] in 1971. Haq Nawaz joined the [[Jamiat Ulama-e-Islam]] and started teaching at a [[madrasah]] in [[Toba Tek Singh]] in 1972. In 1973 he became the [[imam]] and [[khatib]] of a mosque in ''[[mohalla]]'' Piplianwala in the city of [[Jhang Saddar]]. Before he began focusing his preaching against Shia, he was active in the [[Khatm-i Nabuwwat]] movement against Qaadiyanis.<ref name=abouzahab>{{cite book|last=Abou-Zahab|first=Mariam|author-link1=Mariam Abou Zahab|editor1-last=Ahmad|editor1-first=Imtiaz|editor2-last=Reifeld|editor2-first=Helmut|title=Lived Islam in South Asia: Adaptation, Accommodation & Conflict|year=2004|publisher=Social Science Press|location=Jor Bagh, New Delhi|isbn=8187358157|chapter=The Sunni-Shia Conflict in Jhang (Pakistan)}}</ref>\n\nAfter the 1979 [[Iranian Revolution]], Jhangvi began attacking the [[Islamic Republic of Iran]] by accusing it of exporting its revolution. He directed his attacks against Shia beliefs and civilians, as well as against [[Ayatollah Khomeini]], Iran's [[Supreme Leader of Iran|Supreme Leader]]. Locally, he targeted the Shah Jewna family and the district administration and became extremely popular among local residents.<ref name=abouzahab/> Jhangvi also began preaching and became popular among  Sunnis, who were willing to support him in his cause. He became vocal against local Shias.<ref name=abouzahab/> Jhangvi founded Anjuman-i Sipah-i Sahabah in Jhang on 6 September 1985.<ref name=abouzahab/><ref>{{cite book|last1=Murphy|first1=Eamon|title=The Making of Terrorism in Pakistan: Historical and Social Roots of Extremism|date=2013|publisher=Routledge|pages=129, 131|url=https://books.google.com/?id=19mPVOBZ_9YC&dq=haq+nawaz+jhangvi+wahhabi|accessdate=4 May 2016|isbn=9780415565264}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 February 1990, he was asaassinated by unknown militants. His funeral prayer was offered on Friday 23 February 1990 after Namaz e asar. He was buried in Jamia Mehmoodiya Jhang.{{cn|date=January 2019}} Sipah e sahaba members [[Riaz Basra]] and [[Akram Lahori]] formed their own organization in 1996, [[Lashkar-e-Jhangvi]], which was named after Haq Nawaz Jhangvi.{{cn|date=January 2019}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n===Books by him===\n*''K\u0332h\u0332ut\u0324b\u0101t-i am\u012br-i \u02bbaz\u012bmat : b\u0101n\u012b-i Sip\u0101h-i \u1e62a\u1e25\u0101bah Maul\u0101n\u0101 \u1e24aq Nav\u0101z Jhangv\u012b k\u012b ma\u02bbrikatul\u0101r\u0101\u02bc taq\u0101r\u012br k\u0101 majm\u016b\u02bbah''. Collections of speeches.\n===Books about him===\n*''Am\u012br-i \u02bbAz\u012bmat : \u1e25ay\u0101t'' by Mu\u1e25ammad Ily\u0101s B\u0101l\u0101ko\u1e6d\u012b.\n*''Maz\u0332hab ahl al-Sunnat va-al-Jam\u0101\u02bbat aur Maul\u0101n\u0101 \u1e24aq Nav\u0101z Jhangv\u012b k\u012b shah\u0101dat'' by Q\u0101\u1e93\u012b Maz\u0324har \u1e24usain.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Azam Tariq (religious leader)|Azam Tariq]]\n* [[Isar-ul-Haq Qasmi]]\n*[[Malik Ishaq]]\n*[[Moavia Azam Tariq]]\n*[[Masroor Nawaz Jhangvi]]\n*[[Riaz Basra]]\n*[[Zia ur rehman farooqi]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jhangvi, Haq Nawaz}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:1990 deaths]]\n[[Category:Assassinated religious leaders]]\n[[Category:Pakistani religious leaders]]\n[[Category:People from Jhang District]]\n[[Category:Deobandis]]\n[[Category:Shia\u2013Sunni sectarian violence in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Critics of Ahmadiyya]]\n[[Category:Pakistani Islamists]]\n[[Category:Pakistani far-right politicians]]\n\n{{Pakistan-reli-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "GorgeCustersSabre", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiography:c e", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haq_Nawaz_Jhangvi"}
{"title_page": "Noum\u00e9a", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Noumea|the genus of sea slugs|Noumea (gastropod)|the language|Ndrumbea language}}\n{{short description|Capital of New Caledonia}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox French commune\n|name                   = Noum\u00e9a\n|commune status         = [[Communes of France|Commune]]\n|image                  = Noumea centre 1402561139 375c811796 o.jpg\n|caption                = City centre and [[Noum\u00e9a Cathedral]]\n|image coat of arms     = Armoiries Noum\u00e9an fr.png\n|map size               = 270px\n|adjustable map         = noumea.PNG\n|map caption            = Location of the commune (in red)<br>within New Caledonia\n|province               = [[South Province, New Caledonia|South Province]]<br>(provincial seat)\n|INSEE                  = 98818\n|postal code            = 98800\n|mayor                  = [[Sonia Lagarde]]\n|term                   = 2014\u2013present\n|coordinates            = {{coord|-22.2758|166.4580|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation m            = 20\n|elevation min m        = 0\n|elevation max m        = 167\n|area km2               = 45.7\n|urban area km2         = 1,643\n|area footnotes         = <ref name=area>{{cite web|url=http://www.isee.nc/tec/atlas/telechargements/1-territoire-environnement.pdf|title=Tableaux de l'\u00e9conomie cal\u00e9donienne, Chapitre 1 : TERRITOIRE-ENVIRONNEMENT|publisher=ISEE|year=2012|accessdate=2013-10-14|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113161955/http://www.isee.nc/tec/atlas/telechargements/1-territoire-environnement.pdf|archivedate=13 November 2013}}</ref>\n|population             = 94285\n|urban pop              = 182341\n|population date        = 2019 Census<ref name=\"isee.nc\">http://www.isee.nc/component/phocadownload/category/195-donnees?download=768:la-population-legale</ref>\n|ethnic                 = [[European ethnic groups|European]]s 43.23%<br>[[Kanak people|Kanak]]s 23.79%<br>Wallisians and Futunans 6.67%<br>[[Multiracial|Mixed]] 7.87%<br>Other 18.44%\n|ethnic date            = 2014 census\n}}\n\n[[File:Flag of the city of Noum\u00e9a, New Caledonia.png|thumb|upright|Noum\u00e9a city flag, 2011]]\n\n'''Noum\u00e9a''' ({{IPA-fr|numea}}) is the [[capital city|capital]] and largest city of the [[France|French]] [[sui generis collectivity|special collectivity]] of [[New Caledonia]]. It is situated on a peninsula in the south of New Caledonia's main island, [[Grande Terre (New Caledonia)|Grande Terre]], and is home to the majority of the island's [[Europe]]an, [[Polynesia]]n ([[Wallis and Futuna|Wallisians]], [[Wallis and Futuna|Futunians]], [[Tahiti]]ans), [[Indonesia]]n, and [[Vietnamese people|Vietnamese]] populations, as well as many [[Melanesian]]s, [[Ni-Vanuatu]] and [[Kanak people|Kanak]]s who work in one of the [[Oceania|South Pacific]]'s most [[industrialisation|industrialised]] cities. The city lies on a protected deepwater harbour that serves as the chief port for New Caledonia.\n\nAt the September 2019 census, there were 182,341 inhabitants in the metropolitan area of Greater Noum\u00e9a ({{Lang-fr|agglom\u00e9ration du Grand Noum\u00e9a}}), 94,285 of whom lived in the city ([[communes of France|commune]]) of Noum\u00e9a proper.<ref name=pop>{{cite web|url=http://www.isee.nc/component/phocadownload/category/194-structure-de-la-population-et-evolutions?download=1329:population-legale-2014|title=Recensement de la population 2014 \u2013 Populations l\u00e9gales 2014|publisher=ISEE|accessdate=2014-11-16|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20150419171546/http://www.isee.nc/component/phocadownload/category/194-structure-de-la-population-et-evolutions?download=1329:population-legale-2014|archivedate=19 April 2015}}</ref> 67.2% of the population of New Caledonia live in Greater Noum\u00e9a, which covers the communes of Noum\u00e9a, [[Le Mont-Dore (New Caledonia)|Le Mont-Dore]], [[Dumb\u00e9a]] and [[Pa\u00efta]].\n\n==History==\nThe first European to establish a settlement in the vicinity was British trader [[James Paddon]] in 1851. Anxious to assert control of the island, the French established a settlement nearby three years later in 1854, moving from [[Balade (New Caledonia)|Balade]] in the north of the island. This settlement was initially called Port-de-France and was renamed Noum\u00e9a in 1866. The area served first as a [[penal colony]], later as a centre for the exportation of the [[nickel]] and [[gold]] that was mined nearby.\n\nFrom 1904 to 1940 Noum\u00e9a was linked to [[Dumb\u00e9a]] and [[Pa\u00efta]] by the [[Noum\u00e9a-Pa\u00efta railway]], the only railway line that ever existed in New Caledonia.\n\nDuring [[World War II]], Noum\u00e9a served as the headquarters of the [[United States]] military in the South Pacific. The five-sided U.S. military headquarters complex was adopted after the war as the base for a new regional intergovernmental development organisation: the South Pacific Commission, later known as the [[Secretariat of the Pacific Community]], and later still as the Pacific Community.\n\nThe city maintains much of New Caledonia's unique mix of French and old Melanesian culture. Even today the [[United States|US]] wartime military influence lingers, both with the warmth that many New Caledonian people feel towards the United States after experiencing the relative friendliness of American soldiers and also with the names of several of the quarters in Noum\u00e9a. Districts such as \"Receiving\" and \"Robinson\", or even \"Motor Pool\", strike the [[English-speaking world|anglophone]] ear strangely, until the historical context becomes clear.\n\n==Geography==\nThe [[city]] is situated on an irregular, hilly [[peninsula]] near the southeast end of [[New Caledonia]], which is in the south-west [[Pacific Ocean]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2011}}\n\nNeighbourhoods of Noum\u00e9a include:<ref>\"[http://www.ville-noumea.nc/vivre/quartiers.asp Les quartiers] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722112059/http://www.ville-noumea.nc/vivre/quartiers.asp |date=22 July 2011 }}.\" Noum\u00e9a. Retrieved on 12 February 2011.</ref>\n*Rivi\u00e8re-Sal\u00e9e\n*6e km, 7e km, Normandie, and Tina\n*Ducos peninsula:\n**Ducos, Ducos industriel, Kam\u00e9r\u00e9, Koumourou, Logicoop, Numbo, Tindu\n*4e Km, A\u00e9rodrome, Haut Magenta, Magenta, Ou\u00e9mo, and Portes de fer\n*Faubourg Blanchot and Vall\u00e9e des Colons\n*Doniambo, Montagne coup\u00e9e, Montravel, and Vall\u00e9e du tir\n*Artillerie Nord, Centre Ville, Nouville, Quartier Latin, Vall\u00e9e du G\u00e9nie\n*Anse Vata, Artillerie Sud, Baie des Citrons, Motor Pool, N'g\u00e9a, Orphelinat, Receiving, Trianon, and Val Plaisance\n\n==Demographics==\n[[File:Noumea Market.jpg|thumb|250px|A woman at a market in Noum\u00e9a, 2006]]\nThe Greater Noum\u00e9a urban area ({{lang-fr|agglom\u00e9ration du Grand Noum\u00e9a|links=no}}) had a total population of 182,341 inhabitants at the September 2019 census, 94,285 of whom lived in the [[commune in France|commune]] of Noum\u00e9a proper.<ref name=\"isee.nc\"/>\n\nThe Greater Noum\u00e9a urban area is made up of four communes:\n*Noum\u00e9a (94,285 inh.)\n*[[Dumb\u00e9a]] (35,873 inh.), to the north-west of Noum\u00e9a\n*[[Le Mont-Dore (New Caledonia)|Le Mont-Dore]] (27,620 inh.), to the north-east of Noum\u00e9a\n*[[Pa\u00efta]] (24,563 inh.), a suburb to the west of Dumb\u00e9a and the site of [[La Tontouta International Airport]]\n\n===Historical population===\n\n{| rules=\"all\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"4\" style=\"margin:auto; border:1px solid #999; border-right:2px solid #999; border-bottom:2px solid #999; background:#f3fff3;\"\n|-\n! !! 1956!! 1963!! 1969 !! 1976 !! 1983 !! 1989 !! 1996!! 2009 !! 2014 !! 2019\n|-\n| align=center| '''Noum\u00e9a (commune)''' || align=center| 22,235 || align=center| 34,990 || align=center| 41,853 || align=center| 56,078 || align=center| 60,112 || align=center| 65,110 || align=center| 76,293 || align=center| 97,579 || align=center| 99,926 || align=center| 94,285\n|-\n| align=center| '''Greater Noum\u00e9a''' || align=center| 25,204 || align=center| 39,996 || align=center| 50,488 || align=center| 74,335 || align=center| 85,098 || align=center| 97,581 || align=center| 118,823 || align=center| 163,723 || align=center| 179,509 || align=center| 182,341\n|-\n| colspan=\"13\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| <small>Official figures from population censuses.<ref name=pop /><ref name=RP56_09>{{cite web|url=http://www.isee.nc/population/telecharxls/pop-com-56-09.xls|title=Population des communes de la Nouvelle-Cal\u00e9donie de 1956 \u00e0 2009|publisher=ISEE|accessdate=2013-10-14|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121030182852/http://www.isee.nc/population/telecharxls/pop-com-56-09.xls|archivedate=30 October 2012}}</ref></small>\n|}\n\nAverage population growth of the Greater Noum\u00e9a urban area:\n*1956\u20131963: +2,310 people per year (+7.5% per year)\n*1963\u20131969: +1,791 people per year (+4.1% per year)\n*1969\u20131976: +3,349 people per year (+5.6% per year)\n*1976\u20131983: +1,543 people per year (+2.0% per year)\n*1983\u20131989: +2,091 people per year (+2.3% per year)\n*1989\u20131996: +3,020 people per year (+2.8% per year)\n*1996\u20132009: +3,382 people per year (+2.4% per year)\n*2009\u20132014: +3,106 people per year (+1.8% per year)\n*2014\u20132019: +562 people per year (+0.3% per year)\n\n===Migrations===\nThe places of birth of the 179,509 residents in the Greater Noum\u00e9a urban area at the 2014 census were the following:<ref name=censusdetail>{{cite web|url=http://www.isee.nc/component/phocadownload/category/193-recensement?download=1442:rp-2014-population-logement-menages-communes|title=Recensement de la population de 2014 \u2013 Population, m\u00e9nages et logements par communes de Nouvelle Cal\u00e9donie|publisher=ISEE|accessdate=2018-01-02|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171025024348/http://www.isee.nc/component/phocadownload/category/193-recensement?download=1442:rp-2014-population-logement-menages-communes|archivedate=25 October 2017}}</ref>\n*66.7% were born in New Caledonia\n*21.2% in [[Metropolitan France]] and its [[overseas department]]s (other than Wallis-and-Futuna and French Polynesia)\n*6.3% in foreign countries (notably [[Indonesia]], [[Vanuatu]], [[Vietnam]], and [[Algeria]])\n*5.8% in [[Wallis and Futuna]] (essentially) and [[French Polynesia]] (to a lesser extent)\n\n===Ethnic communities===\nThe self-reported ethnic communities of the 179,509 residents in the Greater Noum\u00e9a urban area at the 2014 census were as follows:<ref name=censusdetail />\n*34.48% [[White people|Europeans]]\n*23.43% [[Kanak people|Kanaks]] (original [[Melanesians|Melanesian]] inhabitants of New Caledonia)\n*11.53% [[Wallis and Futuna|Wallisians and Futunians]]\n*10.05% [[multiracial|mixed ethnicity]]\n*20.51% other communities (this group includes in particular the White people of New Caledonia who refused to self-identify as \"Europeans\")\n\n===Languages===\nAt the 2009 census, 98.7% of the population in the Greater Noum\u00e9a urban area whose age was 15 years old and older reported that they could speak [[French language|French]]. 97.1% reported that they could also read and write it. Only 1.3% of the population whose age was 15 years old and older had no knowledge of French.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.isee.nc/population/telecharxls/commune-prov-rp-2009.xls|title=P19 Population de 15 ans et plus, selon le sexe et la connaissance du fran\u00e7ais, par commune et province de r\u00e9sidence|publisher=ISEE|accessdate=2013-10-14|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017182011/http://www.isee.nc/population/telecharxls/commune-prov-rp-2009.xls|archivedate=17 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nAt the same census, 20.8% of the population in the Greater Noum\u00e9a urban area whose age was 15 years old and older reported that they could speak at least one of the [[New Caledonian languages|Kanak languages]]. 4.3% reported that they could understand a Kanak language but not speak it. 74.9% of the population whose age was 15 years old and older had no knowledge of any Kanak language.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.isee.nc/population/telecharxls/commune-prov-rp-2009.xls|title=P21 Population de 15 ans et plus, selon le sexe et la connaissance d'une langue kanak, par commune et province de r\u00e9sidence|publisher=ISEE|accessdate=2013-10-14|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017182011/http://www.isee.nc/population/telecharxls/commune-prov-rp-2009.xls|archivedate=17 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Climate==\nNoum\u00e9a features a [[tropical wet and dry climate]] with hot summers and warm winters. Temperatures are warmer in the months of January, February and March with average highs hovering around 30 degrees Celsius and cooler during the months of July and August where average high temperatures are around 23 degrees Celsius. The capital's [[dry season]] months are September and October. The rest of the year is noticeably wetter. Noum\u00e9a on average receives roughly {{convert|1100|mm|0|abbr=on}} of precipitation annually.\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Noumea, New Caledonia\n|metric first = yes\n|single line = yes\n|Jan high C = 28.9\n|Feb high C = 29.0\n|Mar high C = 28.5\n|Apr high C = 26.9\n|May high C = 25.2\n|Jun high C = 23.8\n|Jul high C = 22.6\n|Aug high C = 22.8\n|Sep high C = 23.8\n|Oct high C = 25.5\n|Nov high C = 27.0\n|Dec high C = 28.2\n|Jan mean C = 26.0\n|Feb mean C = 26.1\n|Mar mean C = 25.6\n|Apr mean C = 24.1\n|May mean C = 22.5\n|Jun mean C = 21.1\n|Jul mean C = 20.0\n|Aug mean C = 20.5\n|Sep mean C = 21.1\n|Oct mean C = 22.4\n|Nov mean C = 23.9\n|Dec mean C = 25.0\n|Jan low C = 23.0\n|Feb low C = 23.2\n|Mar low C = 22.8\n|Apr low C = 21.4\n|May low C = 19.8\n|Jun low C = 18.5\n|Jul low C = 17.3\n|Aug low C = 17.5\n|Sep low C = 17.9\n|Oct low C = 19.2\n|Nov low C = 20.7\n|Dec low C = 21.9\n|Jan precipitation mm = 112.9\n|Feb precipitation mm = 123.1\n|Mar precipitation mm = 134.6\n|Apr precipitation mm = 110.5\n|May precipitation mm = 90.6\n|Jun precipitation mm = 128.7\n|Jul precipitation mm = 73.0\n|Aug precipitation mm = 70.1\n|Sep precipitation mm = 39.2\n|Oct precipitation mm = 53.2\n|Nov precipitation mm = 62.9\n|Dec precipitation mm = 72.7\n|precipitation colour = green\n|Jan precipitation days = 14.2\n|Feb precipitation days = 14.2\n|Mar precipitation days = 17.1\n|Apr precipitation days = 15.0\n|May precipitation days = 16.8\n|Jun precipitation days = 17.3\n|Jul precipitation days = 15.9\n|Aug precipitation days = 13.1\n|Sep precipitation days = 9.6\n|Oct precipitation days = 9.3\n|Nov precipitation days = 10.3\n|Dec precipitation days = 11.3\n|Jan sun = 232.5\n|Feb sun = 209.0\n|Mar sun = 201.5\n|Apr sun = 198.0\n|May sun = 176.7\n|Jun sun = 156.0\n|Jul sun = 182.9\n|Aug sun = 201.5\n|Sep sun = 222.0\n|Oct sun = 251.1\n|Nov sun = 249.0\n|Dec sun = 260.4\n|source 1 = Hong Kong Observatory<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weather.gov.hk/wxinfo/climat/world/eng/australia/pacific/noumea_e.htm|title=Climatological Information for Noumea, New Caledonia|publisher=Hong Kong Observatory|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320072343/http://www.weather.gov.hk/wxinfo/climat/world/eng/australia/pacific/noumea_e.htm|archivedate=20 March 2012}}</ref>|date=August 2010}}\n\n==Economy==\nAlthough Noum\u00e9a has more sunshine days than any other Pacific Island capital and beaches not far from the city centre, it is not currently a major tourist destination.\n\nNoum\u00e9a is, {{As of|2007|lc=y}}, one of the most rapidly growing cities in the Pacific and has experienced a major housing construction boom in the preceding decade. The installation of amenities has kept pace and the municipality boasts a public works programme.\n\n==Transport==\n[[Aircalin]], the international airline of New Caledonia,<ref>\"[http://us.aircalin.com/contact-aircalin.php Contact Us] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090601195747/http://us.aircalin.com/contact-aircalin.php |date=1 June 2009 }}.\" [[Aircalin]]. Retrieved on 2 October 2009.</ref> and [[Air Cal\u00e9donie]] (Aircal), the domestic airline, have their headquarters in the city.<ref>\"[http://air-caledonie.nc:8080/en/ukcontact.htm AIR CAL\u00c9DONIE CONTACTS]{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}.\" [[Air Cal\u00e9donie]]. Retrieved on 2 October 2009.</ref> Aircal's headquarters are on the grounds of [[Noum\u00e9a Magenta Airport]],<ref>\"[http://www.air-caledonie.nc/fr/pdf/carte_renew_nb.pdf Renouvellement de Carte R\u00e9sident] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090530002353/http://www.air-caledonie.nc/fr/pdf/carte_renew_nb.pdf |date=30 May 2009 }}.\" Air Cal\u00e9donie. Retrieved on 8 October 2009.</ref>\nwhich serves local routes. Noum\u00e9a's international airport is [[La Tontouta International Airport]], {{convert|50|km|mi}} from the city.\n\nThe [[Noum\u00e9a-Pa\u00efta railway]], which was the only railway line that ever existed in New Caledonia, was closed in 1940.\n\n==Education==\n[[File:Main building at Nouville campus, University of New Caledonia.png|thumb|250px|[[University of New Caledonia]], Nouville campus]]\n[[File:Exterior view of Bernheim Library, Noum\u00e9a.png|thumb|250px|Bernheim Library exterior]]\n[[File:Interior View 2 of Bernheim Library, Noumea.png|thumb|250px|Bernheim Library interior]]\nThe [[University of New Caledonia]] (UNC) goes back to 1987 when the Universit\u00e9 Fran\u00e7aise du Pacifique (French University of the Pacific) was created, with two centres, one in French Polynesia and the other in New Caledonia. In 1997 the decision was made to split the two parts into separate universities and so in 1999 the Universit\u00e9 de la Nouvelle Cal\u00e9donie and the Universit\u00e9 de la Polyn\u00e9sie Fran\u00e7aise were formed.\n\nUNC welcomes around 3,000 local and international students and 100 professors and researchers each year.<ref>\"{{cite web |url=http://www.univ-nc.nc/propos-de-lunc/presentation |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-01-05 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120119221009/http://www.univ-nc.nc/propos-de-lunc/presentation |archivedate=19 January 2012}} Universit\u00e9 de la Nouvelle-Cal\u00e9donie. Retrieved on 5 January 2012.</ref>\n\nThe ''Biblioth\u00e8que Bernheim'' (Bernheim Library) is located in Noum\u00e9a.<ref>\"[http://www.bernheim.nc/distribution.asp?page=information/vico.asp&inter=0&num=5&parcours=information/paco.asp coordonn\u00e9es & horaires] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110316185105/http://www.bernheim.nc/distribution.asp?page=information%2Fvico.asp&inter=0&num=5&parcours=information%2Fpaco.asp |date=16 March 2011 }}.\" Biblioth\u00e8que Bernheim. Retrieved on 12 February 2011.</ref>\n\n==Twin towns \u2013 sister cities==\n*{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]] ([[Australia]])\n*{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Nice]] ([[Metropolitan France|Metropolitan]] [[France]])<ref name=\"Nice Jumellage\">{{cite web | url = http://www.nice.fr/Collectivites/La-municipalite/Villes-jumelees-avec-la-Ville-de-Nice | title = Villes jumel\u00e9es avec la Ville de Nice | accessdate = 2013-06-24 | publisher = Ville de Nice | language = French | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121029114949/http://nice.fr/Collectivites/La-municipalite/Villes-jumelees-avec-la-Ville-de-Nice | archivedate = 29 October 2012}}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|NZL}} [[Taupo]] ([[New Zealand]])\n\n==Popular culture==\n* New Caledonia was the favorite liberty port in the Pacific of the crew of the ''PT-73'' in the American television series ''[[McHale's Navy]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pro.imdb.com/title/tt0055689/trivia |title=IMDbPro |publisher=Pro.imdb.com |accessdate=2017-11-06}}</ref>\n* Sydney-based author Nathan J. Roche set his 2014 novel ''The Noum\u00e9a Neurosis'', a satirical prose account of cycling, in and around Noum\u00e9a.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thethousands.com.au/sydney/read/nathan-j-roche-the-noumea-neurosis--2 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-01-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170108190232/http://thethousands.com.au/sydney/read/nathan-j-roche-the-noumea-neurosis--2 |archivedate=8 January 2017}}</ref>{{-}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|Noum\u00e9a}}\n*{{Wikivoyage-inline}}\n*[http://www.newcaledoniatourism-south.com/ Tourism New Caledonia (South)]\n*{{in lang|fr}} {{Official website|/www.ville-noumea.nc|Noum\u00e9a's official municipal website}}\n*{{in lang|fr}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20050328065902/http://www.ac-noumea.nc/laperouse/site-hg/site/ Noum\u00e9a: Commune Fran\u00e7aise du Bout du Monde] \u2013 a school project on the geography and history of Noum\u00e9a\n\n{{Administrative divisions of New Caledonia}}\n{{List of Oceanian capitals by region}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Noumea}}\n[[Category:Noum\u00e9a| ]]\n[[Category:Capitals in Oceania]]\n[[Category:Communes of New Caledonia]]\n[[Category:Port cities in Oceania]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Noumea|the genus of sea slugs|Noumea (gastropod)|the language|Ndrumbea language}}\n{{short description|Capital of New Caledonia}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox French commune\n|name                   = Noum\u00e9a\n|commune status         = [[Communes of France|Commune]]\n|image                  = Noumea centre 1402561139 375c811796 o.jpg\n|caption                = City centre and [[Noum\u00e9a Cathedral]]\n|image coat of arms     = Armoiries Noum\u00e9an fr.png\n|map size               = 270px\n|adjustable map         = noumea.PNG\n|map caption            = Location of the commune (in red)<br>within New Caledonia\n|province               = [[South Province, New Caledonia|South Province]]<br>(provincial seat)\n|INSEE                  = 98818\n|postal code            = 98800\n|mayor                  = [[Sonia Lagarde]]\n|term                   = 2014\u2013present\n|coordinates            = {{coord|-22.2758|166.4580|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation m            = 20\n|elevation min m        = 0\n|elevation max m        = 167\n|area km2               = 45.7\n|urban area km2         = 1,643\n|area footnotes         = <ref name=area>{{cite web|url=http://www.isee.nc/tec/atlas/telechargements/1-territoire-environnement.pdf|title=Tableaux de l'\u00e9conomie cal\u00e9donienne, Chapitre 1 : TERRITOIRE-ENVIRONNEMENT|publisher=ISEE|year=2012|accessdate=2013-10-14|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113161955/http://www.isee.nc/tec/atlas/telechargements/1-territoire-environnement.pdf|archivedate=13 November 2013}}</ref>\n|population             = 94285\n|urban pop              = 182341\n|population date        = 2019 Census<ref name=\"isee.nc\">http://www.isee.nc/component/phocadownload/category/195-donnees?download=768:la-population-legale</ref>\n|ethnic                 = [[European ethnic groups|European]]s 43.23%<br>[[Kanak people|Kanak]]s 23.79%<br>Wallisians and Futunans 6.67%<br>[[Multiracial|Mixed]] 7.87%<br>Other 18.44%\n|ethnic date            = 2014 census\n}}\n\n[[File:Flag of the city of Noum\u00e9a, New Caledonia.png|thumb|upright|Noum\u00e9a city flag, 2011]]\n\n'''Noum\u00e9a''' ({{IPA-fr|numea}}) is the [[capital city|capital]] and largest city of the [[France|French]] [[sui generis collectivity|special collectivity]] of [[New Caledonia]]. It is situated on a peninsula in the south of New Caledonia's main island, [[Grande Terre (New Caledonia)|Grande Terre]], and is home to the majority of the island's [[Europe]]an, [[Polynesia]]n ([[Wallis and Futuna|Wallisians]], [[Wallis and Futuna|Futunians]], [[Tahiti]]ans), [[Indonesia]]n, and [[Vietnamese people|Vietnamese]] populations, as well as many [[Melanesian]]s, [[Ni-Vanuatu]] and [[Kanak people|Kanak]]s who work in one of the [[Oceania|South Pacific]]'s most [[industrialisation|industrialised]] cities. The city lies on a protected deepwater harbour that serves as the chief port for New Caledonia.\n\nAt the September 2019 census, there were 182,341 inhabitants in the metropolitan area of Greater Noum\u00e9a ({{Lang-fr|agglom\u00e9ration du Grand Noum\u00e9a}}), 94,285 of whom lived in the city ([[communes of France|commune]]) of Noum\u00e9a proper.<ref name=pop>{{cite web|url=http://www.isee.nc/component/phocadownload/category/194-structure-de-la-population-et-evolutions?download=1329:population-legale-2014|title=Recensement de la population 2014 - Populations l\u00e9gales 2014|publisher=ISEE|accessdate=2014-11-16|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20150419171546/http://www.isee.nc/component/phocadownload/category/194-structure-de-la-population-et-evolutions?download=1329:population-legale-2014|archivedate=19 April 2015}}</ref> 67.2% of the population of New Caledonia live in Greater Noum\u00e9a, which covers the communes of Noum\u00e9a, [[Le Mont-Dore (New Caledonia)|Le Mont-Dore]], [[Dumb\u00e9a]] and [[Pa\u00efta]].\n\n==History==\nThe first European to establish a settlement in the vicinity was British trader [[James Paddon]] in 1851. Anxious to assert control of the island, the French established a settlement nearby three years later in 1854, moving from [[Balade (New Caledonia)|Balade]] in the north of the island. This settlement was initially called Port-de-France and was renamed Noum\u00e9a in 1866. The area served first as a [[penal colony]], later as a centre for the exportation of the [[nickel]] and [[gold]] that was mined nearby.\n\nFrom 1904 to 1940 Noum\u00e9a was linked to [[Dumb\u00e9a]] and [[Pa\u00efta]] by the [[Noum\u00e9a-Pa\u00efta railway]], the only railway line that ever existed in New Caledonia.\n\nDuring [[World War II]], Noum\u00e9a served as the headquarters of the [[United States]] military in the South Pacific. The five-sided U.S. military headquarters complex was adopted after the war as the base for a new regional intergovernmental development organisation: the South Pacific Commission, later known as the [[Secretariat of the Pacific Community]], and later still as the Pacific Community.\n\nThe city maintains much of New Caledonia's unique mix of French and old Melanesian culture. Even today the [[United States|US]] wartime military influence lingers, both with the warmth that many New Caledonian people feel towards the United States after experiencing the relative friendliness of American soldiers and also with the names of several of the quarters in Noum\u00e9a. Districts such as \"Receiving\" and \"Robinson\", or even \"Motor Pool\", strike the [[English-speaking world|anglophone]] ear strangely, until the historical context becomes clear.\n\n==Geography==\nThe [[city]] is situated on an irregular, hilly [[peninsula]] near the southeast end of [[New Caledonia]], which is in the south-west [[Pacific Ocean]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2011}}\n\nNeighbourhoods of Noum\u00e9a include:<ref>\"[http://www.ville-noumea.nc/vivre/quartiers.asp Les quartiers] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722112059/http://www.ville-noumea.nc/vivre/quartiers.asp |date=22 July 2011 }}.\" Noum\u00e9a. Retrieved on 12 February 2011.</ref>\n*Rivi\u00e8re-Sal\u00e9e\n*6e km, 7e km, Normandie, and Tina\n*Ducos peninsula:\n**Ducos, Ducos industriel, Kam\u00e9r\u00e9, Koumourou, Logicoop, Numbo, Tindu\n*4e Km, A\u00e9rodrome, Haut Magenta, Magenta, Ou\u00e9mo, and Portes de fer\n*Faubourg Blanchot and Vall\u00e9e des Colons\n*Doniambo, Montagne coup\u00e9e, Montravel, and Vall\u00e9e du tir\n*Artillerie Nord, Centre Ville, Nouville, Quartier Latin, Vall\u00e9e du G\u00e9nie\n*Anse Vata, Artillerie Sud, Baie des Citrons, Motor Pool, N'g\u00e9a, Orphelinat, Receiving, Trianon, and Val Plaisance\n\n==Demographics==\n[[File:Noumea Market.jpg|thumb|250px|A woman at a market in Noum\u00e9a, 2006]]\nThe Greater Noum\u00e9a urban area ({{lang-fr|agglom\u00e9ration du Grand Noum\u00e9a|links=no}}) had a total population of 182,341 inhabitants at the September 2019 census, 94,285 of whom lived in the [[commune in France|commune]] of Noum\u00e9a proper.<ref name=\"isee.nc\"/>\n\nThe Greater Noum\u00e9a urban area is made up of four communes:\n*Noum\u00e9a (94,285 inh.)\n*[[Dumb\u00e9a]] (35,873 inh.), to the north-west of Noum\u00e9a\n*[[Le Mont-Dore (New Caledonia)|Le Mont-Dore]] (27,620 inh.), to the north-east of Noum\u00e9a\n*[[Pa\u00efta]] (24,563 inh.), a suburb to the west of Dumb\u00e9a and the site of [[La Tontouta International Airport]]\n\n===Historical population===\n\n{| rules=\"all\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"4\" style=\"margin:auto; border:1px solid #999; border-right:2px solid #999; border-bottom:2px solid #999; background:#f3fff3;\"\n|-\n! !! 1956!! 1963!! 1969 !! 1976 !! 1983 !! 1989 !! 1996!! 2009 !! 2014 !! 2019\n|-\n| align=center| '''Noum\u00e9a (commune)''' || align=center| 22,235 || align=center| 34,990 || align=center| 41,853 || align=center| 56,078 || align=center| 60,112 || align=center| 65,110 || align=center| 76,293 || align=center| 97,579 || align=center| 99,926 || align=center| 94,285\n|-\n| align=center| '''Greater Noum\u00e9a''' || align=center| 25,204 || align=center| 39,996 || align=center| 50,488 || align=center| 74,335 || align=center| 85,098 || align=center| 97,581 || align=center| 118,823 || align=center| 163,723 || align=center| 179,509 || align=center| 182,341\n|-\n| colspan=\"13\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| <small>Official figures from population censuses.<ref name=pop /><ref name=RP56_09>{{cite web|url=http://www.isee.nc/population/telecharxls/pop-com-56-09.xls|title=Population des communes de la Nouvelle-Cal\u00e9donie de 1956 \u00e0 2009|publisher=ISEE|accessdate=2013-10-14|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121030182852/http://www.isee.nc/population/telecharxls/pop-com-56-09.xls|archivedate=30 October 2012}}</ref></small>\n|}\n\nAverage population growth of the Greater Noum\u00e9a urban area:\n*1956\u20131963: +2,310 people per year (+7.5% per year)\n*1963\u20131969: +1,791 people per year (+4.1% per year)\n*1969\u20131976: +3,349 people per year (+5.6% per year)\n*1976\u20131983: +1,543 people per year (+2.0% per year)\n*1983\u20131989: +2,091 people per year (+2.3% per year)\n*1989\u20131996: +3,020 people per year (+2.8% per year)\n*1996\u20132009: +3,382 people per year (+2.4% per year)\n*2009\u20132014: +3,106 people per year (+1.8% per year)\n*2014\u20132019: +562 people per year (+0.3% per year)\n\n===Migrations===\nThe places of birth of the 179,509 residents in the Greater Noum\u00e9a urban area at the 2014 census were the following:<ref name=censusdetail>{{cite web|url=http://www.isee.nc/component/phocadownload/category/193-recensement?download=1442:rp-2014-population-logement-menages-communes|title=Recensement de la population de 2014 - Population, m\u00e9nages et logements par communes de Nouvelle Cal\u00e9donie|publisher=ISEE|accessdate=2018-01-02|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171025024348/http://www.isee.nc/component/phocadownload/category/193-recensement?download=1442:rp-2014-population-logement-menages-communes|archivedate=25 October 2017}}</ref>\n*66.7% were born in New Caledonia\n*21.2% in [[Metropolitan France]] and its [[overseas department]]s (other than Wallis-and-Futuna and French Polynesia)\n*6.3% in foreign countries (notably [[Indonesia]], [[Vanuatu]], [[Vietnam]], and [[Algeria]])\n*5.8% in [[Wallis and Futuna]] (essentially) and [[French Polynesia]] (to a lesser extent)\n\n===Ethnic communities===\nThe self-reported ethnic communities of the 179,509 residents in the Greater Noum\u00e9a urban area at the 2014 census were as follows:<ref name=censusdetail />\n*34.48% [[White people|Europeans]]\n*23.43% [[Kanak people|Kanaks]] (original [[Melanesians|Melanesian]] inhabitants of New Caledonia)\n*11.53% [[Wallis and Futuna|Wallisians and Futunians]]\n*10.05% [[multiracial|mixed ethnicity]]\n*20.51% other communities (this group includes in particular the White people of New Caledonia who refused to self-identify as \"Europeans\")\n\n===Languages===\nAt the 2009 census, 98.7% of the population in the Greater Noum\u00e9a urban area whose age was 15 years old and older reported that they could speak [[French language|French]]. 97.1% reported that they could also read and write it. Only 1.3% of the population whose age was 15 years old and older had no knowledge of French.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.isee.nc/population/telecharxls/commune-prov-rp-2009.xls|title=P19 Population de 15 ans et plus, selon le sexe et la connaissance du fran\u00e7ais, par commune et province de r\u00e9sidence|publisher=ISEE|accessdate=2013-10-14|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017182011/http://www.isee.nc/population/telecharxls/commune-prov-rp-2009.xls|archivedate=17 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nAt the same census, 20.8% of the population in the Greater Noum\u00e9a urban area whose age was 15 years old and older reported that they could speak at least one of the [[New Caledonian languages|Kanak languages]]. 4.3% reported that they could understand a Kanak language but not speak it. 74.9% of the population whose age was 15 years old and older had no knowledge of any Kanak language.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.isee.nc/population/telecharxls/commune-prov-rp-2009.xls|title=P21 Population de 15 ans et plus, selon le sexe et la connaissance d'une langue kanak, par commune et province de r\u00e9sidence|publisher=ISEE|accessdate=2013-10-14|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017182011/http://www.isee.nc/population/telecharxls/commune-prov-rp-2009.xls|archivedate=17 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Climate==\nNoum\u00e9a features a [[tropical wet and dry climate]] with hot summers and warm winters. Temperatures are warmer in the months of January, February and March with average highs hovering around 30 degrees Celsius and cooler during the months of July and August where average high temperatures are around 23 degrees Celsius. The capital's [[dry season]] months are September and October. The rest of the year is noticeably wetter. Noum\u00e9a on average receives roughly {{convert|1100|mm|0|abbr=on}} of precipitation annually.\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Noumea, New Caledonia\n|metric first = yes\n|single line = yes\n|Jan high C = 28.9\n|Feb high C = 29.0\n|Mar high C = 28.5\n|Apr high C = 26.9\n|May high C = 25.2\n|Jun high C = 23.8\n|Jul high C = 22.6\n|Aug high C = 22.8\n|Sep high C = 23.8\n|Oct high C = 25.5\n|Nov high C = 27.0\n|Dec high C = 28.2\n|Jan mean C = 26.0\n|Feb mean C = 26.1\n|Mar mean C = 25.6\n|Apr mean C = 24.1\n|May mean C = 22.5\n|Jun mean C = 21.1\n|Jul mean C = 20.0\n|Aug mean C = 20.5\n|Sep mean C = 21.1\n|Oct mean C = 22.4\n|Nov mean C = 23.9\n|Dec mean C = 25.0\n|Jan low C = 23.0\n|Feb low C = 23.2\n|Mar low C = 22.8\n|Apr low C = 21.4\n|May low C = 19.8\n|Jun low C = 18.5\n|Jul low C = 17.3\n|Aug low C = 17.5\n|Sep low C = 17.9\n|Oct low C = 19.2\n|Nov low C = 20.7\n|Dec low C = 21.9\n|Jan precipitation mm = 112.9\n|Feb precipitation mm = 123.1\n|Mar precipitation mm = 134.6\n|Apr precipitation mm = 110.5\n|May precipitation mm = 90.6\n|Jun precipitation mm = 128.7\n|Jul precipitation mm = 73.0\n|Aug precipitation mm = 70.1\n|Sep precipitation mm = 39.2\n|Oct precipitation mm = 53.2\n|Nov precipitation mm = 62.9\n|Dec precipitation mm = 72.7\n|precipitation colour = green\n|Jan precipitation days = 14.2\n|Feb precipitation days = 14.2\n|Mar precipitation days = 17.1\n|Apr precipitation days = 15.0\n|May precipitation days = 16.8\n|Jun precipitation days = 17.3\n|Jul precipitation days = 15.9\n|Aug precipitation days = 13.1\n|Sep precipitation days = 9.6\n|Oct precipitation days = 9.3\n|Nov precipitation days = 10.3\n|Dec precipitation days = 11.3\n|Jan sun = 232.5\n|Feb sun = 209.0\n|Mar sun = 201.5\n|Apr sun = 198.0\n|May sun = 176.7\n|Jun sun = 156.0\n|Jul sun = 182.9\n|Aug sun = 201.5\n|Sep sun = 222.0\n|Oct sun = 251.1\n|Nov sun = 249.0\n|Dec sun = 260.4\n|source 1 = Hong Kong Observatory<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weather.gov.hk/wxinfo/climat/world/eng/australia/pacific/noumea_e.htm|title=Climatological Information for Noumea, New Caledonia|publisher=Hong Kong Observatory|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320072343/http://www.weather.gov.hk/wxinfo/climat/world/eng/australia/pacific/noumea_e.htm|archivedate=20 March 2012}}</ref>|date=August 2010}}\n\n==Economy==\nAlthough Noum\u00e9a has more sunshine days than any other Pacific Island capital and beaches not far from the city centre, it is not currently a major tourist destination.\n\nNoum\u00e9a is, {{As of|2007|lc=y}}, one of the most rapidly growing cities in the Pacific and has experienced a major housing construction boom in the preceding decade. The installation of amenities has kept pace and the municipality boasts a public works programme.\n\n==Transport==\n[[Aircalin]], the international airline of New Caledonia,<ref>\"[http://us.aircalin.com/contact-aircalin.php Contact Us] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090601195747/http://us.aircalin.com/contact-aircalin.php |date=1 June 2009 }}.\" [[Aircalin]]. Retrieved on 2 October 2009.</ref> and [[Air Cal\u00e9donie]] (Aircal), the domestic airline, have their headquarters in the city.<ref>\"[http://air-caledonie.nc:8080/en/ukcontact.htm AIR CAL\u00c9DONIE CONTACTS]{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}.\" [[Air Cal\u00e9donie]]. Retrieved on 2 October 2009.</ref> Aircal's headquarters are on the grounds of [[Noum\u00e9a Magenta Airport]],<ref>\"[http://www.air-caledonie.nc/fr/pdf/carte_renew_nb.pdf Renouvellement de Carte R\u00e9sident] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090530002353/http://www.air-caledonie.nc/fr/pdf/carte_renew_nb.pdf |date=30 May 2009 }}.\" Air Cal\u00e9donie. Retrieved on 8 October 2009.</ref>\nwhich serves local routes. Noum\u00e9a's international airport is [[La Tontouta International Airport]], {{convert|50|km|mi}} from the city.\n\nThe [[Noum\u00e9a-Pa\u00efta railway]], which was the only railway line that ever existed in New Caledonia, was closed in 1940.\n\n==Education==\n[[File:Main building at Nouville campus, University of New Caledonia.png|thumb|250px|[[University of New Caledonia]], Nouville campus]]\n[[File:Exterior view of Bernheim Library, Noum\u00e9a.png|thumb|250px|Bernheim Library exterior]]\n[[File:Interior View 2 of Bernheim Library, Noumea.png|thumb|250px|Bernheim Library interior]]\nThe [[University of New Caledonia]] (UNC) goes back to 1987 when the Universit\u00e9 Fran\u00e7aise du Pacifique (French University of the Pacific) was created, with two centres, one in French Polynesia and the other in New Caledonia. In 1997 the decision was made to split the two parts into separate universities and so in 1999 the Universit\u00e9 de la Nouvelle Cal\u00e9donie and the Universit\u00e9 de la Polyn\u00e9sie Fran\u00e7aise were formed.\n\nUNC welcomes around 3,000 local and international students and 100 professors and researchers each year.<ref>\"{{cite web |url=http://www.univ-nc.nc/propos-de-lunc/presentation |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-01-05 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120119221009/http://www.univ-nc.nc/propos-de-lunc/presentation |archivedate=19 January 2012}} Universit\u00e9 de la Nouvelle-Cal\u00e9donie. Retrieved on 5 January 2012.</ref>\n\nThe ''Biblioth\u00e8que Bernheim'' (Bernheim Library) is located in Noum\u00e9a.<ref>\"[http://www.bernheim.nc/distribution.asp?page=information/vico.asp&inter=0&num=5&parcours=information/paco.asp coordonn\u00e9es & horaires] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110316185105/http://www.bernheim.nc/distribution.asp?page=information%2Fvico.asp&inter=0&num=5&parcours=information%2Fpaco.asp |date=16 March 2011 }}.\" Biblioth\u00e8que Bernheim. Retrieved on 12 February 2011.</ref>\n\n==Twin towns \u2013 sister cities==\n*{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]] ([[Australia]])\n*{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Nice]] ([[Metropolitan France|Metropolitan]] [[France]])<ref name=\"Nice Jumellage\">{{cite web | url = http://www.nice.fr/Collectivites/La-municipalite/Villes-jumelees-avec-la-Ville-de-Nice | title = Villes jumel\u00e9es avec la Ville de Nice | accessdate = 2013-06-24 | publisher = Ville de Nice | language = French | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121029114949/http://nice.fr/Collectivites/La-municipalite/Villes-jumelees-avec-la-Ville-de-Nice | archivedate = 29 October 2012}}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|NZL}} [[Taupo]] ([[New Zealand]])\n\n==Popular culture==\n* New Caledonia was the favorite liberty port in the Pacific of the crew of the ''PT-73'' in the American television series ''[[McHale's Navy]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pro.imdb.com/title/tt0055689/trivia |title=IMDbPro |publisher=Pro.imdb.com |accessdate=2017-11-06}}</ref>\n* Sydney-based author Nathan J. Roche set his 2014 novel ''The Noum\u00e9a Neurosis'', a satirical prose account of cycling, in and around Noum\u00e9a.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thethousands.com.au/sydney/read/nathan-j-roche-the-noumea-neurosis--2 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-01-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170108190232/http://thethousands.com.au/sydney/read/nathan-j-roche-the-noumea-neurosis--2 |archivedate=8 January 2017}}</ref>{{-}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|Noum\u00e9a}}\n*{{Wikivoyage-inline}}\n*[http://www.newcaledoniatourism-south.com/ Tourism New Caledonia (South)]\n*{{in lang|fr}} {{Official website|/www.ville-noumea.nc|Noum\u00e9a's official municipal website}}\n*{{in lang|fr}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20050328065902/http://www.ac-noumea.nc/laperouse/site-hg/site/ Noum\u00e9a: Commune Fran\u00e7aise du Bout du Monde] \u2013 a school project on the geography and history of Noum\u00e9a\n\n{{Administrative divisions of New Caledonia}}\n{{List of Oceanian capitals by region}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Noumea}}\n[[Category:Noum\u00e9a| ]]\n[[Category:Capitals in Oceania]]\n[[Category:Communes of New Caledonia]]\n[[Category:Port cities in Oceania]]\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixeddashesusing ascript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Noum%C3%A9a"}
{"title_page": "The Assets", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = The Assets\n| image                    = TheAssetsIntertitle.png\n| genre                    = [[Thriller (genre)|Thriller]]\n| based_on                 = {{based on|''Circle of Treason''}}\n| creator                  = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Sandra Grimes]]\n* [[Jeanne Vertefeuille]]\n}}\n| writer                   =\n| director                 =\n| starring                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Jodie Whittaker]]\n* [[Paul Rhys]]\n* [[Harriet Walter]]\n* [[Ralph Brown]]\n* [[Stuart Milligan]]\n* [[Christina Cole]]\n* [[Catalina Denis]] \n* [[Lex Shrapnel]] \n}}\n| composer                 = H. Scott Salinas\n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 1\n| num_episodes             = 8\n| list_episodes            = #Episodes\n| executive_producer       = {{Plainlist|\n*Morgan Hertzan\n*Rudy Bednar\n*Andrew Chapman}}\n| producer                 = James Elkus\n| cinematography           = Darran Tiernan\n| editor                   = Steve Mirkovich\n| camera                   = \n| runtime                  = 42 minutes\n| company                  = {{Plainlist|\n*Baltic Films Services\n*[[List of production companies owned by the American Broadcasting Company#Lincoln Square Productions|Lincoln Square Productions]]}}\n| channel                  = [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]\n| picture_format           = [[720p]] ([[High-definition television|HDTV]])\n| audio_format             = [[Stereo]]\n| first_aired              = {{start date|2014|1|02}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|2014|8|03}}\n| website                  = http://abc.go.com/shows/the-assets/\n}}\n\n'''''The Assets''''' is an eight-part American drama television miniseries that aired on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2013/11/19/abc-releases-midseason-schedule-betrayal-canceled-revenge-moves-to-10pm-suburgatory-premieres-january-15/216813|title=ABC Releases Midseason Schedule: 'Betrayal' in Limbo, 'Revenge' Moves to 10PM, + 'Suburgatory' Premieres January 15|last=Kondolojy|first=Amanda|work=TV by the Numbers|date=November 19, 2013|accessdate=November 21, 2013}}</ref> The series was based on the book ''Circle of Treason: A CIA Account of Traitor [[Aldrich Ames]] and the Men He Betrayed'' by retired [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] officers [[Sandra Grimes]] and [[Jeanne Vertefeuille]]. The series was executively produced by Morgan Hertzan, Rudy Bednar and Andrew Chapman.\n\n''The Assets'' received mixed reviews from critics. [[IMDb]] awarded it a 7.5 out of 10, [[Amazon Prime]] awarded it a 4.5 out of 5, and [[Metacritic]] awarded the series a \"mixed or average\" score of 58 out of 100, based on reviews by fifteen critics.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/the-assets |title=The Assets : Season 1 |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=May 30, 2014}}</ref> The series was picked up by [[Alibi (TV channel)|Alibi]] for broadcast in the [[United Kingdom]], with broadcast set for Summer 2018, ahead of Jodie Whittaker's debut as [[Thirteenth Doctor|The Doctor]] in ''[[Doctor Who]]''.<ref>https://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2018-05-09/jodie-whittakers-american-cia-thriller-the-assets-gets-uk-premiere/</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Jodie Whittaker]] as [[Sandra Grimes]]\n* [[Paul Rhys]] as [[Aldrich Ames]]\n* [[Harriet Walter]] as [[Jeanne Vertefeuille]]\n* [[Ralph Brown]] as Wallace Austin\n* [[Stuart Milligan]] as Arthur O'Neill\n* [[Christina Cole]] as Louisa Tilton\n* [[Catalina Denis]] as Rosario Ames\n* [[Lex Shrapnel]] as Mitch Weaver\n* [[Julian Ovenden]] as Gary Grimes\n* [[Goran Kosti\u0107]] as Victor Cherkashin\n* [[John Lynch (actor)|John Lynch]] as Vitaly Yurchenko\n* Amelia Clarkson as Kelly Grimes\n* [[Akie Kotabe]] as Eric D'Amaro\n\n==Episodes==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:70%;\"\n|- style=\"color:white;\"\n! style=\"background: #9A0700;\" |No.\n! style=\"background: #9A0700;\" |Title\n! style=\"background: #9A0700;\" |Directed by\n! style=\"background: #9A0700;\" |Written by\n! style=\"background: #9A0700;\" |Original air date\n! style=\"background: #9A0700;\" |U.S. viewers<br />(millions)\n|-\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 1\n |Title = My Name is Aldrich Ames\n |DirectedBy = [[Jeff T. Thomas]]\n |WrittenBy = Drew Chapman\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2014|1|02}}\n |Viewers = 3.77<ref name=\"1.01\">{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/01/06/thursday-final-ratings-the-big-bang-theory-two-and-a-half-men-the-millers-adjusted-down/226379|title=Thursday Final Ratings: 'The Big Bang Theory', 'Two and a Half Men' & 'The Taste' Adjusted Up; 'The Millers' Adjusted Down|work=TV by the Numbers|last=Bibel|first=Sara|date=January 6, 2014|accessdate=January 6, 2014}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary = In 1985, CIA agent [[Aldrich Ames]] hands over top-secret files to the Russian embassy in Washington, D.C. At a counter-intelligence meeting, agent [[Sandra Grimes]] discusses a high-ranking KGB officer, who gave the CIA valuable intel in the 1970s. A money drop is scheduled, but the asset and his handler are both captured by the KGB. The handler is released but the asset is shot dead. The whole situation bothers Sandra and she investigates. She learns the asset at the money drop was a [[Shill|plant]], as the real asset was a spy and had likely been captured long before the drop. She fears a mole in the CIA. Meanwhile, in Italy, a man claiming to be a senior counter-intelligence colonel in the KGB calls the U.S. embassy to say he wishes to defect.\n |LineColor = 9A0700\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 2\n |Title = Jewel in the Crown\n |DirectedBy = Jeff T. Thomas\n |WrittenBy = Drew Chapman\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2014|1|09}}\n |Viewers = 2.92<ref name=\"1.02\">{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/01/10/thursday-final-ratings-the-big-bang-theory-parks-and-recreation-adjusted-up/228284|title=Thursday Final Ratings: 'The Big Bang Theory' & 'Parks and Recreation' Adjusted Up|last=Bibel|first=Sara|work=TV by the Numbers|date=January 10, 2014|accessdate=January 10, 2014}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary = [[Vitaly Yurchenko]] defects to the U.S. Ames is assigned to be his initial debriefing agent. Ames is fearful Yurchenko will expose him as a spy, but the man doesn't recognize him. However, he does confirm a mole in the CIA. Sandra is concerned about their asset, General [[Dmitri Polyakov]], known as \"Top Hat\", but he is later warned by his son of traitors. Yurchenko knows the traitor's code name, Mr. Robert, whom he has heard has problems with money, relationships, and drinking, and is now ex-CIA. The CIA is now focused on [[Edward Lee Howard]], who was fired two years ago. \n |LineColor = 9A0700\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 3\n |Title = Trip to Vienna\n |RTitle=<ref name=Futon/>\n |DirectedBy = Adam Lucas Feinstein\n |WrittenBy = Alex Berger\n |OriginalAirDate = {{start date|2014|6|21}}\n |Viewers = 1.25<ref name=\"tvseriesfinale1\">{{cite web|url=http://tvseriesfinale.com/tv-show/the-assets-season-one-ratings-31092/ |title=The Assets on ABC: latest ratings &#124; canceled + renewed TV shows |publisher=TV Series Finale |date= |accessdate=2014-08-20}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary = Yurchenko fingers Edward Lee Howard as the mole but Sandy remains concerned about other likely leaks. Sandy does her best to show that her asset General Polyakov is trying to get in touch with the CIA. With a distracted CIA, Ames forms an improbable bond with Yurchenko.\n |LineColor = 9A0700\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 4\n |Title = What's Done is Done\n |RTitle=<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/listings/20140609abc10/ |title=(#104) What's Done is Done |publisher=The Futon Critic |accessdate=June 11, 2014}}</ref>\n |DirectedBy = Rudy Bednar\n |WrittenBy = Bruce Terris\n |OriginalAirDate = {{start date|2014|6|28}}\n |Viewers = 1.46<ref name=\"tvseriesfinale1\"/>\n |ShortSummary = Jeanne and Sandy are at odds over Jeanne's review of their operations. Ames is unsettled by Jeanne's presence as the Soviets are pressuring him for more information. The pressure at home on Ames is his wife's compulsive shopping habits.\n |LineColor = 9A0700\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 5\n |Title = Check Mate\n |RTitle=<ref name=Futon/>\n |DirectedBy = Trygve Allister Diesen\n |WrittenBy = Karen Stillman\n |OriginalAirDate = {{start date|2014|7|27}}\n |Viewers = \n |ShortSummary = Sandy and Jeanne continue to clash over Sandy's review of the skills and techniques employed by agency's spies. When a man known as GTPROLOGUE contacts the agency claiming vital information concerning a communications breach, Sandy has her doubts. Ames' transfer request to Rome is approved.\n |LineColor = 9A0700\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 6\n |Title = A Small Useless Truth\n |RTitle=<ref name=Futon/>\n |DirectedBy = Trygve Allister Diesen\n |WrittenBy = Sarah Byrd\n |OriginalAirDate = {{start date|2014|7|27}}\n |Viewers = \n |ShortSummary = With differences aside, Sandy and Jeanne proceed ahead with the mole hunt. Sandy finds out General Polyakov has been compromised. Ames gets ready for a high-stakes polygraph exam.\n |LineColor = 9A0700\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 7\n |RTitle=<ref name=Futon/>\n |Title = The Straw Poll\n |DirectedBy = Peter Medak\n |WrittenBy = Bruce Terris\n |OriginalAirDate = {{start date|2014|8|3}}\n |Viewers = \n |ShortSummary = The CIA remains committed to find those responsible for their assets' compromise, even after the fall of the Berlin Wall and the collapse of communism. Sandy is sure the likely person is Ames but is having trouble convincing the rest of the task force. Back in America after living a charmed life in Rome, Ames finds it hard to maintain that lifestyle.\n |LineColor = 9A0700\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 8\n |Title = Avenger\n |RTitle=<ref name=Futon>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/showatch/assets/listings/ |title=Shows A-Z - assets, the on abc |publisher=The Futon Critic |accessdate=June 9, 2014}}</ref>\n |DirectedBy = Peter Medak \n |WrittenBy = Drew Chapman\n |OriginalAirDate = {{start date|2014|8|3}}\n |Viewers = \n |ShortSummary = Even though the task force is convinced of Ames' guilt, Sandy looks for definitive proof so the Justice Department can proceed. Sandy's dedication to the job tries on Gary's patience. Ames is finally caught and brought to justice, but he mulls what \u2014 if anything \u2014 he's willing to say.\n |LineColor = 9A0700\n}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official|http://abc.go.com/shows/the-assets/}}\n*{{IMDb title|3074646|The Assets}}\n*{{tv.com show|the-assets|The Assets}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Assets, The}}\n[[Category:Fiction set in 1985]]\n[[Category:2010s American drama television series]]\n[[Category:2014 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2014 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:American Broadcasting Company original programming]]\n[[Category:Television series about the Cold War]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Espionage television series]]\n[[Category:Television programs based on books]]\n[[Category:Television series based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Television series set in 1985]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Television series by Disney\u2013ABC Domestic Television]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = The Assets\n| image                    = TheAssetsIntertitle.png\n| genre                    = [[Thriller (genre)|Thriller]]\n| based_on                 = {{based on|''Circle of Treason''}}\n| creator                  = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Sandra Grimes]]\n* [[Jeanne Vertefeuille]]\n}}\n| writer                   =\n| director                 =\n| starring                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Jodie Whittaker]]\n* [[Paul Rhys]]\n* [[Harriet Walter]]\n* [[Ralph Brown]]\n* [[Stuart Milligan]]\n* [[Christina Cole]]\n* [[Catalina Denis]] \n* [[Lex Shrapnel]] \n}}\n| composer                 = H. Scott Salinas\n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 1\n| num_episodes             = 8\n| list_episodes            = #Episodes\n| executive_producer       = {{Plainlist|\n*Morgan Hertzan\n*Rudy Bednar\n*Andrew Chapman}}\n| producer                 = James Elkus\n| cinematography           = Darran Tiernan\n| editor                   = Steve Mirkovich\n| camera                   = \n| runtime                  = 42 minutes\n| company                  = {{Plainlist|\n*Baltic Films Services\n*[[List of production companies owned by the American Broadcasting Company#Lincoln Square Productions|Lincoln Square Productions]]}}\n| channel                  = [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]\n| picture_format           = [[720p]] ([[High-definition television|HDTV]])\n| audio_format             = [[Stereo]]\n| first_aired              = {{start date|2014|1|02}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|2014|8|03}}\n| website                  = http://abc.go.com/shows/the-assets/\n}}\n\n'''''The Assets''''' is an eight-part American drama television miniseries that aired on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2013/11/19/abc-releases-midseason-schedule-betrayal-canceled-revenge-moves-to-10pm-suburgatory-premieres-january-15/216813|title=ABC Releases Midseason Schedule: 'Betrayal' in Limbo, 'Revenge' Moves to 10PM, + 'Suburgatory' Premieres January 15|last=Kondolojy|first=Amanda|work=TV by the Numbers|date=November 19, 2013|accessdate=November 21, 2013}}</ref> The series was based on the book ''Circle of Treason: A CIA Account of Traitor [[Aldrich Ames]] and the Men He Betrayed'' by retired [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] officers [[Sandra Grimes]] and [[Jeanne Vertefeuille]]. The series was executively produced by Morgan Hertzan, Rudy Bednar and Andrew Chapman.\n\n''The Assets'' received mixed reviews from critics. [[IMDb]] awarded it a 7.5 out of 10 [[amazon prime]] awarded it a 4.5 out of 5 [[Metacritic]] awarded the series a \"mixed or average\" score of 58 out of 100, based on reviews by fifteen critics.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/the-assets |title=The Assets : Season 1 |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=May 30, 2014}}</ref> The series was picked up by [[Alibi (TV channel)|Alibi]] for broadcast in the [[United Kingdom]], with broadcast set for Summer 2018, ahead of Jodie Whittaker's debut as [[Thirteenth Doctor|The Doctor]] in ''[[Doctor Who]]''.<ref>https://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2018-05-09/jodie-whittakers-american-cia-thriller-the-assets-gets-uk-premiere/</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Jodie Whittaker]] as [[Sandra Grimes]]\n* [[Paul Rhys]] as [[Aldrich Ames]]\n* [[Harriet Walter]] as [[Jeanne Vertefeuille]]\n* [[Ralph Brown]] as Wallace Austin\n* [[Stuart Milligan]] as Arthur O'Neill\n* [[Christina Cole]] as Louisa Tilton\n* [[Catalina Denis]] as Rosario Ames\n* [[Lex Shrapnel]] as Mitch Weaver\n* [[Julian Ovenden]] as Gary Grimes\n* [[Goran Kosti\u0107]] as Victor Cherkashin\n* [[John Lynch (actor)|John Lynch]] as Vitaly Yurchenko\n* Amelia Clarkson as Kelly Grimes\n* [[Akie Kotabe]] as Eric D'Amaro\n\n==Episodes==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:70%;\"\n|- style=\"color:white;\"\n! style=\"background: #9A0700;\" |No.\n! style=\"background: #9A0700;\" |Title\n! style=\"background: #9A0700;\" |Directed by\n! style=\"background: #9A0700;\" |Written by\n! style=\"background: #9A0700;\" |Original air date\n! style=\"background: #9A0700;\" |U.S. viewers<br />(millions)\n|-\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 1\n |Title = My Name is Aldrich Ames\n |DirectedBy = [[Jeff T. Thomas]]\n |WrittenBy = Drew Chapman\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2014|1|02}}\n |Viewers = 3.77<ref name=\"1.01\">{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/01/06/thursday-final-ratings-the-big-bang-theory-two-and-a-half-men-the-millers-adjusted-down/226379|title=Thursday Final Ratings: 'The Big Bang Theory', 'Two and a Half Men' & 'The Taste' Adjusted Up; 'The Millers' Adjusted Down|work=TV by the Numbers|last=Bibel|first=Sara|date=January 6, 2014|accessdate=January 6, 2014}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary = In 1985, CIA agent [[Aldrich Ames]] hands over top-secret files to the Russian embassy in Washington, D.C. At a counter-intelligence meeting, agent [[Sandra Grimes]] discusses a high-ranking KGB officer, who gave the CIA valuable intel in the 1970s. A money drop is scheduled, but the asset and his handler are both captured by the KGB. The handler is released but the asset is shot dead. The whole situation bothers Sandra and she investigates. She learns the asset at the money drop was a [[Shill|plant]], as the real asset was a spy and had likely been captured long before the drop. She fears a mole in the CIA. Meanwhile, in Italy, a man claiming to be a senior counter-intelligence colonel in the KGB calls the U.S. embassy to say he wishes to defect.\n |LineColor = 9A0700\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 2\n |Title = Jewel in the Crown\n |DirectedBy = Jeff T. Thomas\n |WrittenBy = Drew Chapman\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2014|1|09}}\n |Viewers = 2.92<ref name=\"1.02\">{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/01/10/thursday-final-ratings-the-big-bang-theory-parks-and-recreation-adjusted-up/228284|title=Thursday Final Ratings: 'The Big Bang Theory' & 'Parks and Recreation' Adjusted Up|last=Bibel|first=Sara|work=TV by the Numbers|date=January 10, 2014|accessdate=January 10, 2014}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary = [[Vitaly Yurchenko]] defects to the U.S. Ames is assigned to be his initial debriefing agent. Ames is fearful Yurchenko will expose him as a spy, but the man doesn't recognize him. However, he does confirm a mole in the CIA. Sandra is concerned about their asset, General [[Dmitri Polyakov]], known as \"Top Hat\", but he is later warned by his son of traitors. Yurchenko knows the traitor's code name, Mr. Robert, whom he has heard has problems with money, relationships, and drinking, and is now ex-CIA. The CIA is now focused on [[Edward Lee Howard]], who was fired two years ago. \n |LineColor = 9A0700\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 3\n |Title = Trip to Vienna\n |RTitle=<ref name=Futon/>\n |DirectedBy = Adam Lucas Feinstein\n |WrittenBy = Alex Berger\n |OriginalAirDate = {{start date|2014|6|21}}\n |Viewers = 1.25<ref name=\"tvseriesfinale1\">{{cite web|url=http://tvseriesfinale.com/tv-show/the-assets-season-one-ratings-31092/ |title=The Assets on ABC: latest ratings &#124; canceled + renewed TV shows |publisher=TV Series Finale |date= |accessdate=2014-08-20}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary = Yurchenko fingers Edward Lee Howard as the mole but Sandy remains concerned about other likely leaks. Sandy does her best to show that her asset General Polyakov is trying to get in touch with the CIA. With a distracted CIA, Ames forms an improbable bond with Yurchenko.\n |LineColor = 9A0700\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 4\n |Title = What's Done is Done\n |RTitle=<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/listings/20140609abc10/ |title=(#104) What's Done is Done |publisher=The Futon Critic |accessdate=June 11, 2014}}</ref>\n |DirectedBy = Rudy Bednar\n |WrittenBy = Bruce Terris\n |OriginalAirDate = {{start date|2014|6|28}}\n |Viewers = 1.46<ref name=\"tvseriesfinale1\"/>\n |ShortSummary = Jeanne and Sandy are at odds over Jeanne's review of their operations. Ames is unsettled by Jeanne's presence as the Soviets are pressuring him for more information. The pressure at home on Ames is his wife's compulsive shopping habits.\n |LineColor = 9A0700\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 5\n |Title = Check Mate\n |RTitle=<ref name=Futon/>\n |DirectedBy = Trygve Allister Diesen\n |Writ