thira]].Imayavar([[Deva (Hinduism)|Devas]]) came to this place prior to [[Yudhishthira]] and hence the deity here is referred as Imayavarappar.<ref>{{cite book|title=Thulasi garland|publisher=Bharatiya Vidya Bhavan|year=1998|first=Gouri Lakshmi |last=Bayi|page=244}}</ref> There is another version that the Pandavas worshipped the idols during the reign and started installing them in different places during the end of the reign.<ref>{{cite book|title=Theerthayathra: A Pilgrimage Through Various Temples|publisher=Bharathiya Vidya Bhavan|last=K.|first=Sukumaran|year=2009|isbn=9788172763633}}</ref>\n|-\n|83\n|[[Mayapiran Temple|Thiruppuliyur]]\n|[[Puliyur Mahavishnu Temple|Thripuliyur]],<br>[[Alappuzha District]],<br>[[Kerala]]<br>{{coord|9.42723| 76.81732}}\n|[[File:Puliyoor.JPG|130px|center]] \n|Sri Porkodi Naachiyaar sametha Sri Maayapiran Perumal\n|\n|-\n|84\n|[[Aranmula Parthasarathy Temple|Thiruvaranvilai]]\n|[[Aranmula]],<br>[[Pathanamthitta District]],<br>[[Kerala]]<br>{{coord|9.35542| 76.76033}}\n|[[File:Aranmula Temple.JPG|130px|center]] \n|Sri Padmasani Naachiyaar sametha Sri Kuralappan Perumal\n|\n|-\n|85\n|[[Pambanaiappan Temple|Thiruvanvandoor]]\n|[[Thiruvanvandoor]],<br>[[Alappuzha District]],<br>[[Kerala]]<br>{{coord|9.35542| 76.76031}}\n|[[File:Thiruvanvandoor Pambanaiappan Temple 1.JPG|130px|center]] \n|Sri Kamalavalli Naachiyaar sametha Sri Paambanaiyappan Perumal\n|It is one of the five ancient shrines in the [[Chengannur]] area of Kerala, connected with the legend of [[Mahabharata]], where the five [[Pandavas]] are believed to have built one temple each; this temple is believed to have been built by [[Nakula]]. Earliest references to this temple appear in the poems and hymns composed by the greatest of Alvar saints - [[Nammalvar]], in circa 800 AD. Stone inscriptions in the temple date it back to the Second [[Chera dynasty|Chera]] Empire (800 - 1102 AD).<ref>{{cite book|title=Temples of Kerala, page 304-305|last=S.|first= Jayashanker|publisher= Direc